{"questionId":"9066770","questionHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">State <strong>one</strong> advantage of using fusion reactions rather than fission to generate electrical power.</span></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><em>Any one of:</em><br>fuel is inexpensive/readily available <strong>[✔]</strong><br>no/less radioactive waste is formed <strong style=\"color:#000000;font-family:Verdana , Arial , Helvetica , sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:bold;letter-spacing:normal;text-align:left;text-decoration:none;text-indent:0px;white-space:normal;\">[✔]</strong><br>lower risk of accidents/large-scale disasters&nbsp;<strong style=\"color:#000000;font-family:Verdana , Arial , Helvetica , sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:bold;letter-spacing:normal;text-align:left;text-decoration:none;text-indent:0px;white-space:normal;\">[✔]</strong><br>impossible/harder to use for making materials for nuclear weapons&nbsp;<strong style=\"color:#000000;font-family:Verdana , Arial , Helvetica , sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:bold;letter-spacing:normal;text-align:left;text-decoration:none;text-indent:0px;white-space:normal;\">[✔]</strong><br>larger amounts of energy released per unit mass&nbsp;<strong style=\"color:#000000;font-family:Verdana , Arial , Helvetica , sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:bold;letter-spacing:normal;text-align:left;text-decoration:none;text-indent:0px;white-space:normal;\">[✔]</strong><br>does not require a critical mass&nbsp;<strong style=\"color:#000000;font-family:Verdana , Arial , Helvetica , sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:bold;letter-spacing:normal;text-align:left;text-decoration:none;text-indent:0px;white-space:normal;\">[✔]</strong><br>can be used continuously&nbsp;<strong style=\"color:#000000;font-family:Verdana , Arial , Helvetica , sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:bold;letter-spacing:normal;text-align:left;text-decoration:none;text-indent:0px;white-space:normal;\">[✔]</strong></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><strong>Note</strong>:&nbsp;Accept “higher specific energy for fusion”.</span></em></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Do <strong>not</strong> accept “no/less waste produced for fusion”.</span></em></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Accept specific example for a disaster.</span></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9066770","referenceCode":"19M.3.hl.TZ2.b","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"State one advantage of using fusion reactions rather than fission to generate electrical power.","paper":"3","level":"hl","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Options","Options","C: Energy","C.3 Nuclear fusion and fission","Options","C: Energy"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}